[SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:)

**Expected Behavior**:
M1 and M2 could produce identical IL.

**Actual Behavior**:
The IL generated is more akin to:
```C#
    public void M1(int i)
    {
        <>y__InlineArray1<int> buffer = default(<>y__InlineArray1<int>);
        <PrivateImplementationDetails>.InlineArrayElementRef<<>y__InlineArray1<int>, int>(ref buffer, 0) = i;
        Use(<PrivateImplementationDetails>.InlineArrayAsReadOnlySpan<<>y__InlineArray1<int>, int>(ref buffer, 1));
    }

    public void M2(int i)
    {
        Use(new ReadOnlySpan<int>(ref i));
    }
```
The JIT is able to produce exactly the same thing for both, but the IL for the former is more complicated and requires the compiler synthesize the `<>y__InlineArray1<T>` type if it wouldn't otherwise be necessary.

This is related to the following Razor user reported bugs:

https://github.com/dotnet/razor/issues/9721
https://github.com/dotnet/razor/issues/9942

There are a couple of issues there, but focusing specifically on the fact that cursor is left after the inserted ```async``` keyword when the user completes ```await```, that can be fixed by adding the cursor position marker ```$0``` at the end of the supplied snippet edit text. E.g. when the user has

```
@code {
   Task DoSomethingAsync() 
   {
      await$$
   }
}
```
and they  complete ```await``` as shown above, the edit in the supplied completion item is ```async Task DoSomethingAsync()\r\n    {        await```. If instead Roslyn would supply edit text ```async Task DoSomethingAsync()\r\n    {        await$0``` the cartet would be placed in the correct position.

The underlying code in Razor does create a minimal edit and we end up with just ```async``` as NewText, but that would be avoided as well if $0 was supplied at the end of the edit. I tried manually patching it from Razor side just to test it, and it seems to work well.
